2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a short form of the personal name <i>Adelhard</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’. Compare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘ardour’; borne in the Middle Ages by various rulers in south-west Wales, including  Rhys ap Tewdur  (  d. 1093 ) and  Rhys ap Gruffudd  (  1132–97 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Reece","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Rhys . The name is now in widespread and frequent use outside Wales, in many cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the given name."]},{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Welsh Rhys, in some cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the Welsh given name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rhys ap Hywel was born in 1274, in Gladestry, Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Hywel Ap Meurig, was 34 and his mother, de Clanvow, was 34. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mrs. Rhys ap Hywel. He died on 11 April 1328, in Cantref, Breconshire, Wales, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1274–11 April 1328":"1274–11. aprill 1328","1260–1286":"1260–1286","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270